By Mr. DiDomenico, a petition (accompanied by resolve, Senate, No. 346) of Sal N.
DiDomenico that provisions be made for an investigation and study by a special commission
(including members of the General Court) to study the funding of high-quality early education.
Education.
The Commonwealth of Massachusetts
_______________
In the One Hundred and Ninety-Fourth General Court
(2025-2026)
_______________
Resolve establishing a commission to study the funding of high-quality early education and care
in Massachusetts.
1 Resolved, that a special commission is hereby established to study and make
2 recommendations for adequately and equitably funding high-quality early education and care in
3 the Commonwealth so that all children build the foundational skills they need to thrive in school
4 and life.
5 Resolved, that the study shall determine the feasibility of creating a foundation budget for
6 early education and care. The scope of the study shall include all current and potential funding
7 streams for the continuation of the mixed-provider delivery of formal and informal programs for
8 infants, toddlers, preschoolers, and school-age children during out-of-school time. The study
9 shall include, but not be limited to, the following areas: (i) determine the true cost of delivering
10 high-quality early education and care in Massachusetts, taking into account provider type, age
11 group, region, high-need population levels, and fair staff wages; (ii) examine all existing and
12 potential funding streams including federal, state, local, philanthropic, employers, and families
13 and how best to coordinate them; (iii) explore the opportunity to build upon the Commonwealth
1 of 4

14 Preschool Partnership Initiative (CPPI) through municipal, state and potentially private
15 investments to create increased access through local partnerships and collaborations; (iv) review
16 the successes and challenges of the utilization of the Commonwealth Cares for Children (C3)
17 Grant Program by providers; (v) investigate methods to design funding streams to address
18 providers’ underfunding or unmet needs such as child mental and behavioral health services,
19 early intervention and special education services, capital improvements, summer learning,
20 transportation, and other needs as determined by the commission; (vi) examine effective ways to
21 create diverse and robust career pathways for early educators, including cross-sectoral
22 approaches, apprenticeship opportunities, access to career training, accessible and equitable
23 credential and endorsement opportunities, and approaches to tie pathways to improving staff
24 compensation; and (viii) any other aspect related to the subject matter of the commission that the
25 commission deems necessary to fulfill its mandate. During its study, the commission shall
26 ensure that the voices and perspectives of diverse providers, parents, and vulnerable stakeholders
27 from the early education and care system are elevated and considered by all members.
28 Resolved, the commission shall consist of the following members or their designees: the
29 house and senate chairs of the joint committee on education, who shall serve as co-chairs; the
30 house and senate chairs of the joint committee on children, families and persons with disabilities;
31 1 member to be appointed by the president of the senate; 1 member to be appointed by the
32 speaker of the house; 1 member to be appointed by the chair of the senate committee on ways
33 and means; 1 member to be appointed by the chair of the house committee on ways and means;
34 the secretary of education; the commissioner of the department of early education and care; the
35 commissioner of the department of elementary and secondary education; the commissioner of the
36 department of higher education; the secretary of the executive office of health and human
